Dao's is the nearly the best Vietnamese food in town and I've been there for dinner many times.  I took the too-cool-for-tuesday lunch crowd there last week and it was SLOW.  The food was great, but it honestly was unfortunately slow.  There were only two tables populated, the other table had their food already, and we waited about 30 minutes for our food.  Highly recommended Vietnamese food.  They do have Chinese dishes and some Thai, but don't be picky get Vietnamese food and you will be happy.  Just don't go for lunch unless you have lots of time!  I hate giving them less than 5 because it's really good food, nice staff, clean, they have boba and they have free wifi.

Thanks Community Food Bank for letting me and some coworkers contribute our painting of some nice murals to go up in the store!  This place offers food to those in need but also serves as a food store where profits made from purchases are used to support the charity services.  They also do interesting things like garden education and arrange a farmer's market.

One of the best Mexican restaurants in Philly hands down. Although it's not traditional Mexican they do a great job of cooking up innovative new takes on the classics such as crab and lobster tacos with mango salsa. They also make fresh guacamole to order, though at $12 a serving it's way over priced. There is definitely something for everyone here with poultry, meat, seafood, and vegetarian options. The drink menu is solid for a Mexican place with the required margaritas and tequila. The restaurant again takes a new twist on the old favorites with blood orange margaritas, pomegranite margaritas, no tequila margaritas, and some interesting sangria combinations. Service was pretty attentive except for refilling the water. The only things that keep this place from getting 5 stars is that it is amazingly loud and there are way too many smokers for my taste given that the bar is in the center of the tables. Be sure to check out the photo booth if you go in.

Melograno is a nice BYOB tucked away near Fitler Square. They specialize in Tuscan cuisine and have a nice array or classic Italian options on their menu. The decor is nice and warm making you feel welcome inthe small space. Pasta is homemade and outstanding, they do a good job of cooking it to the right texture. In addition to the nice selection of pastas they have several salads to choose from and both fish and meat dishes. The seafood in particular was excellent, very fresh, and mixed with nice herbs and sauces. The waiter swore by the tiramisu but we went with the chocolate cake and apple tart which was really more like a cake. Both were good and capped off a very good dinner.

On a recent cross country road trip,  I had the pleasure of spending an evening on "Lower Broad" and happened into the Legends Corner Bar.  It is a fantastic bar that has no-cover live music from the early evening until the early morning.  The bands tend to play for tips, and have an amazing ability to play request on demand.  You will be hard pressed to find better musicianship or setting for relaxing with your friends, having a friendly drink (or two!) and striking up a conversation with any of folks within earshot.   As for food, it is typical bar fare..but the pizza was pretty good after a long night of honky tonk fun!

Being a first time to Nashville,  I am very thankful to have stumbled into Tootsie's Orchid Lounge.   We had a great time taking in some local talent (Chris Jensen) who was as good as any I have heard take the stage, and had three times as much energy as any 19 year old singer-songwriter should.   The walls of this place literally talk to you, as autographed photos of anyone who has ever been "somebody" return your wondered gaze.   When you snap back to reality,  the prettiest and friendliest servers are ready to bring you anything your heart desires along with a smile and a story if you have the time.   The Orchid Lounge is definitely worth a quick stop, or a longer one if you have the time.  You will not be dissappointed!

Worth the hype.  Whole wheat crust makes you feel like youre doing something good for your body besides consuming lots of processed carbs (youre really not, but thats hardly the point).  The crust MAKES the pizza and they do it right here.  A must do in Isla Vista between seeing drunk chicks boobs and avoiding STD's.
see review of the Phoenix location.  Great ... absolutely top-notch steakhouse experience.  Wouldn't have expected it in Tucson, and it was a real treat.

Jon Stocking, founder and owner, says he "created this company in an effort to spread awareness and to make an impact on the growing number of plant and animal species that are disappearing from the Earth every single day".  He formerly worked on a tuna boat where he "witnessed unimaginable disregard of the ocean by the crew".  He spent hours freeing baby dolphins & other marine life from the nets.  So he founded the Endangered Species Chocolate Company & donates 10% of profits to worthwhile organizations that can make a difference.  I buy the product at Whole Foods and, embarrassingly, eat a TON of this delicious inexpensive chocolate.  There are many varieties:  I have in my hand The Harp Seal Bar:  smooth white chocolate.  Inside the label you will read about the plight of the animal pictured on the front.  There is The Grizzly Bar, dark chocolate.  And The Polar Bar, Belgian white chocolate with macadamia nuts - one of my favorites.  Other bars include:  Chimpanzee, Gorilla, Rainforest, Dolphin, Elephant, Manatee and Harp Seal.  The product contains healthy ingredients, no bad additives of course.  www.chocolatebar.com  Bravo to you, Jon!

this place once made me very ill

but pretty good going down

if you like deep dish and live in tucson,
may be your best bet

wait, no, go to zach's!!!

the food is okay (fairly greasy and boring and not vegetarian friendly)

but the ice cream rocks

the best thing is probably the casual old diner feel about this place

the thing i miss most by no longer living in tucson

spinach and artichoke dip in the bread bowl

but the sandwiches rock!

also, they still have rc

very cute

basic italian food

but sitting outside
with the fairy lights
is perfect
for a first date

angelina's special

and limeade, 

please!!

my family still raves about this place 3 years later!!!

the sandwiches are quite remarkable

as well as the pizza cookies

good for lunch or dinner

but beware of crowds

They made it all easy - circle drive, the baggage handlers, the concierge, valets - even with our then four-month-old baby, we moved about with total ease.  The room was large and our older one had plenty of room to play on the floor and run around.  Great wi-fi service.  Nice pool.  And best of all, water pressure in the shower that beat us senseless.

It's in an area with a lot of conference activity, so plenty of restaurants, shopping and entertainment a short walk away.

my favourite italian restaurant in the states

the fetuccine romana is amazing

and always get the house dressing

yum

There are many quality restaurants in downtown Santa Barbara, but only a handful have the charm of Roy. This sweet little restaurant is named after the owner and head chef, Roy. They offer a lot of seasonal and local food and wine. The staff are attentive and helpful. They tend to serve food pretty late (12-1am). The vibe is mellow, the booths are comfy and the food is always delish. The location is convenient and you can park nearby either on the street or at one of the city lots off State St.

Update: I revisited Roy in June 2007. They expanded and there's more seating available, but the vibe is still cozy and intimate. We really enjoyed the soup, homemade bread and vino (of course!).

Screw you, Subway.  Move over Togo's.  Port of Subs is probably a good enough reason for me to want to move to Reno.  I know, RENO!  But I never miss a stop into my favorite sub place in the world when I'm in Nevada to visit my Emm-er-ly. They mix their mayo and mustard which i really like for some reason, and all meats and cheeses are sliced thin as paper right as you order your sandwich.  Pickle slices are those lengthwise kind so you get some pickle in every bite.  They just get every detail about the sandwich PERFECT, and I just love it.

Sushi Ten is a great place.  It is definitely the best place to go for sushi on the east side of town.  Consistently good over the few times I've been there in the last few years, and still good now, so it must be yelped.  Also, it's cheap for sushi.  Huge portions and relatively low prices.  You may be shocked at the size of the pieces of fish you get if you've been to the more well known or expensive places.

This store is very cool.  It's located in a strip mall by Best Buy and looks like it would be tiny from the street, but it's a decently sized store with lots of gear that is fun to look at.  It's pretty expensive but you can probably find what you need and spend plenty of time playing with stuff or buying stuff you don't need.

A good place to get stuff that Target or Wal-Mart don't have or stock well enough.  I guess since it is a sporting goods store though, a lot of the stuff you can find elsewhere is too expensive, like sweats or a swim suit.

I can't believe I haven't yelped Saver's, disgusted with myself and everyone else who has also not yelped it.  This place is awesome.  I've bought a $1 golf club that worked out better than any high-end new club I've tried, for example.  Whenever anything means a chance to get stuff I need at Saver's I am happy.

I was at the U of A with a friend, needed coffee and I think this is the place we went in.  It looked like a standard university area coffee place, I didn't want or get coffee.  My bottled water was awesome, but shadowed by the impossibly good latte I tasted.  Very, very good.  I don't think I've had a better coffee drink ever, and I don't even drink lattes.  The problem is that it seemed like there were a bunch of chatty sorority types stomping up and down the store to talk to this friend and go back and talk to the other one and go back again... also, beware the live coffee house music.  The musicians weren't bad, but the place isn't suited to handle the decibels and went from comfortable conversation to yelling "WHAT DID YOU SAY."

While I can't add anything about the ownership, I can say that the General Tso's chicken was good enough that the General himself is probably grinnin' in his grave.  

Unfortunately, I have to spend the next several days in Horsham, PA for work - at least I have another dining experience at Mandarin to look forward to.  Not bad as 99% of the other restaurants in a 10 mile radius seem to be Olive Garden-esque chains.

Delicious find outside of Philly! Incredible hot & spicy seafood soup, steamed dumplings, and succulent Peking duck with all of the fixings! 

Great service, BYOB, and lots of awards for this amazing restaurant with 2 full menus: Mandarin/Szechuan and Japanese menus. Margaret Kuo is famous for her Chinese food so I would steer you to that menu.

Somehow I was led to believe this was a luxury hotel near QVC studios. Unfortunately I was wrong on the "luxury" assumption - our suite's rollaway bed had the most hideous bed linens, and there were not enough power outlets for business travelers. But in its defense, the customer service was great and tney bailed us out of being stuck when absolutely no taxi company was open at  1am and they had someone drive to pick us up. Their shuttle service is excellent - everything else would send you back to Philly for luxury accomodations.

Der brauhausen!  Ok, so I'm a sucker for German places with a good selection of beer (think Essen Haus, Madison).  Otto's is just down the road from my hotel (traveling for work - why else would I be in Horsham?), and a colleague wanted to try it.  Fantastic decision.  The food was great, they have 23 beers on tap, and the service was friendly.

I had the pork tenderloin dusseldorf, which is a tasty pork dish in a mustard sauce with crispy onions.  It was by no means gourmet and I have breathe that would stun a charging yak, but it was definitely worth the price.

The best turnout of Too Cool for Tuesday so far was at Kyo Sushi.  I had sashimi and a soft shell crab roll and it was decent, medium portions.  What makes the place very good I think is the location, closest sushi place to where I work.  It's in Rita Ranch by the Safeway there.

I'm rating the lounge only! (I heard the restaurant is good too, but overpriced.) This is a great place for really good cocktails and live jazz music. Thursdays there are appetizer specials and $5 martinis! Can't beat that! My fave is the chocolate diva. mmmmmmm The only thing though, is that it's a little cramped in there. They could use more space!

Ever since Rasheed Wallace answered a reporter's question "Can you get a good cheesesteak in Portland?" with an assertive "Aw, hell no!" I've fantasized about making a pilgrimage to Sheed's hometown and seeking out the real thing.

This last April I sampled Geno's legendary sandwich.

My companion and I decided that we would order our sandwich "with whiz," which in Philly steak parlance means "Give me a steak sandwich with onions and Cheese Whiz." Other options are available, and some folks swear by American or Provolone cheese, but the legendary cheesesteak of my dreams, the cheesesteak of arcane power, the cheesesteak vilified by dead child molester and frugal gourmet Jeff Smith, the cheesesteak I've spied numerous times dancing across my always-tuned-to-the-Food Network television screen, has the bright yellow goo, the almost-dairy product that Kraft Corporation christened Cheese Whiz. I don't even like Cheese Whiz.

Well, it was pretty damn good.  Tidy, not the sloppy monster of a sandwich that Pat's King of Steaks offers, but good, nonetheless. The service, of course, was extra speedy, and the the young woman who handed us our drinks was incredibly rude.  I was expecting this.

Overall, a good, not-too-messy sandwich.

Last April, I traveled to Philly to sample Pat's and Geno's steaks in my quest for the most authentic, delicious, cheeze-whizzyish cheeseteak in the city of brotherly love and limited beer sales.

Geno's was good, tidy, almost genteel. A nice mix of  whiz, onions, and meat.

Pat's, on the other hand, won points for sheer abundance. This thing was big. And messy (see photos). With about twice as much filling as Geno's, the flavor of the steak took center stage. I found Pat's to be a bit tastier, probably because the beef flavor came through more clearly. However, the bread was overwhelmed. I was overwhelmed too, with Cheese Whiz, mostly. Too much of the whiz is not necessarily a good thing.

I gave a marginal win to Pat's on the basis of bounty, (and because they had a better selection of condiments and ruder staff), but I would really need to eat a few more steaks to decide on a definite favorite. Right now, Geno's sounds pretty good.

The medical anomalies collection here is amazing. I wished that I visited the museum before medical school b/c you can learn a lot from the exhibits... but it's never too late to check out the fascinating siamese twins exhibits which includes a cast of the famous Chang and Eng twins, there's also an extensive collection of "obstructed objects" which include everything from pins to pistachio nuts, teratogenic birth defects,  and beautifully preserved dissections of the human body. Truly one of the neatest museums in the city.

Nothing beats tax-free shopping! And if you're planning to stop by the Philadelphia area, you must check out King of Prussia's Shopping Complex.  The stores here offer the latest trends typically found in the city, Nordstrom's has an amazing shoe collection and the cool stores here include BCBG, Urban Outfitters, Free People, Deisel, Armani Exchange, Versace, Banana Republic, H&M, Bose, Borders, several Anne Taylors. There's also many restaurants here such as the Cheesecake Factory, Morton's Steakhouse, California Pizza Kitchen, and they have really fun food court that reminds me of Water Tower's Foodlife in Chicago.

Ribeye steak=excellent, juicy and medium rare like I asked
Beans=good, a little "al dente" with bacon and  pepper flavor
Salad=ok (eh, it's a salad)
Baked potato=excellent
Bread=tasty, lightly toasted and lots of butter
I was quite satiated after this meal. This is a great place for steak and ribs. So good in fact, I ate the entire 14 oz. of steak. Then again that might have to do with the fact that I had nothing else to eat for the entire day. Yay for post-Halloween party hangovers! Whatever the case, I highly recommend this place. It's never ridiculously busy (like Pinnacle Peak and places like that) and the service is pretty good. How are people vegetarian? Seriously....I'll eat twice the steak to make up for the meat they aren't consuming.

This is a great place for lunch because they have decent food, large portions, and many lunch specials for $4.  I have been turned into somewhat of a Chinese food snob, so I have to mention if you are also this way don't expect anything amazing.  But it's cheap for lunch and decent if your friends don't know the difference.

I don't know, I was told about this place by two people, but I wasn't impressed.  I didn't feel comfortable in the store as nobody really seemed interested in helping.  Got a very low energy feel even as I considered a bike much more expensive than I said I wanted to buy.  I was surprised at this experience after it being recommended twice.  I guess that's what Yelp is good for.
This local music store really sucks.  Loses extra points for lame "the last real record store", or something like that, claim.  More like "the last real closet full of crap."

It got me thinking since I am housing a "refugee" and I think Siam Cafe is the most wonderful space in New Orleans, that I know of. You go up these stairs there is a bar in the centerby the wall pillows on the floor and these double doors that spill outside it's fantastic. I hope to go back sometime soon.

THE MOST AWESOME PLACE ON EARTH, I MISS IT!


That was my honest opinion, until I heard that Jacque is the biggest asshole ever!

He pays his employees very little, and remember Austin Leslie, the man famous for his  fried chicken. Well, I heard that he asked Jacque for a raise and he fired him! Unfortunately Austin had a heart attack in the super dome during the hurricane and died 2 weeks later. How sad! 

Not only that but I heard that he's in Thailand right now, and he's going to fire all of his employees, and hire Thai employees because he can pay them very little. Can you believe this! That sucks when a restaurant is really good and then you hear a story like this.

I spent the summer of 2003 in Columbia, Missouri. It was pretty awful. One of the bright spots was visiting St. Louis and going to Cecil Whittaker's. The toasted ravioli is amazing! St. Louis style pizza? Not bad!

But the real draw here is Monday Mania, when all food items are half off. Bring a bunch of friends and eat until you cannot eat anymore!

Went here for brunch. Seemed like a cool place in the middle of Manayunk and I'm sure it's a fun bar scene but do not go for the food. They do have some authentic cajun menu items, but the execution and service were abysmal. Menu descriptions were misleading and special requests were ignored. We had a fly in our water and asked for another glass, the second glass we received had debris in it.

If I could give this zero stars I would.

Solid homey Italian food in a byob setting. The waitstaff and manager were very accomodating. The food was solid homestyle Italian, not much flair and small portions, but very delicious. Some of the best tomato based sauces in Philly can be found here. The restaurant is very loud and there can be a long line, even at an early hour, but all in all I would recommend the place. Only three desserts to choose from and I thought the apple one was by far the best.

One of the top BYOB's in the city. Django is located near South Street in a small space. It's reasonably quiet with good, attentive service. The menu is put together seasonally with all fresh ingredients. It's very comprehensive and has something for everyone. We had some amazing savory dishes and the food at the neighboring tables looked equally good. A sample of some of what was on our menu includes goat cheese gnocchi, pumpkin infused risotto, duck breast, bison steak, scallops with lobster hash, and halibut pasta. I'm not doing them justice in their descriptions, but it gives an idea of what's out there. Desserts were fantastic as well.

The best pizza by delivery I've had in Philly in my year living here. Admittedly that is a very small sample size, but the pizza was good. Gusto's gives you a pretty big menu of unconventional pizza toppings. They have a nice tangy tomato sauce and use the right amount of cheese. The crust isn't perfect, it's a little salty, but all in all its pretty darn good. They were courteous in taking my order on the phone and got the pizza here within the specified 40 minutes of time. It was cold when it got here, but not too bad. Also tried their BBQ calzone which was good but would have been better with a more flavorful BBQ sauce.

HUGE delicious SANDWICHES! I LOVE the names of some of them, like Brad's Beef and Stan's Stack. Can I get those with extra dressing? ; )
The desserts are great too! Try a chocolate cake, or perhaps a fruit tart, or a magic bar....
Friendly staff, but the owner is creepy. Competitive prices with the other salons in the area.
Great place for food and drinks. Lots of tv's and college atmosphere. Go for your birthday and get a fish bowl. Yum!

If you're in St. Louis, you must visit the arch. It's an amazing sight that you won't see anywhere else. The documentary they show at the arch is kind of cool as well. Go to the top if you want a spectacular view. Beware - the elevator is TINY.
A St. Louis classic. Great pizza and friendly staff. Vegetarian's beware, the sauce has sausage already in it.
Same as panera everywhere else. Great food for decent prices. The only half-way healthy "fastfood" place in the area.

This is a MUST in St. Louis. However don't go here for the friendly staff, good food, or fun atmosphere. This place is a joke! They will need to buzz you in the door to come in and try the delightful SLINGER. Eat right or don't eat at all!

Typical landing bar, but always a good time. They have a little bit of everything here. A brewery bar area, pool tables, video games, outdoor patio, and decent sized dance floor. Great for large groups who are looking for variety.
Always a good time here. Great outdoor patio in the summer. Has awesome live music and plenty of room to sit and have a drink.

This place USED to be tons of fun, but has quickly gone down hill. It is located directly next to Busch stadium (bonus!), but has quickly attracted a crowd larger than it can handle. If you go here, plan to stand outside and wait in long lines for a beer.

Great food and great atmosphere. Worth the trip out to Clayton. Tons right around this place for a little bar hopping. They have excellent food and a decent menu. I recommend the frozen drinks. They are delicious!
Good sized mall with lots of excellent stores. Gets VERY crowded over the holidays, but what mall doesn't? Not great food here. Plan to eat before you shop. Hands down, best mall in St. Louis area.

Great little Japanese restaurant in Santa Barbara - there are some cheaper deals around but this place is worth spending the extra money for a little bit more quality.  Located on State Street - it's very ideal and very convenient.
This is one of the reasons why I miss Santa Barbara - great location in Hollister and great food - great salads and even better dessert.

This place has the best view ever - right on the beach and the food is delish!  I once hosted a dinner banquet here for about 35 people and the wait staff was amazing - the service was excellent and working setting up the menu was so easy.  From the calamari to their steak to their desserts - everything is fabulous.

I once set up a formal event here for about 60+ people five years ago and the service was great - easy to work with and the food was definately interesting.  I had the vegetarian entree which was pretty good and the view is great from here, as well.
Decent food but the location is great - right on the pier and beautiful view.  Decent food, pricey prices but awesome view.
This place is a hidden gem - love it and used to go there all the time for breakfasts/brunches.  They even have tables in the sand so wear flip flops - service is amazing and food is even better.
Decent food, decent service - super convenient since it's right on State street though.  The main reason why I'd come back are for the drinks - they like to make them extra strong.

I love this place for their garlic bread - food isn't bad either, but the garlic bread.  As a college student back in the day - my friends and I would go there, stuff ourselves with their garlic bread and water and then, order an appetizer or entree and split it between ourselves and some dessert, too.  We shared that, too :)  SUper convenient location right on State Street.

Great place - hosted another dinner party here for 30+ people and they were very polite and the service/wait staff was great!  Prices are just right for fantastic mouth-watering Mexican food.  And I heart tequilla - they have tequilla for me :)

How in God's name have I wound up spending so much freaking time in Philadelphia suburbia?!@?  Damnit!  

If you have to be there, Iron Hill can serve as a refuge and place to drink you cares away.  Hell, why stop at cares?  You're in North Wales, which is by Horsham - may as well drink away your temporal memories and ability to differentiate colors.

Apologies to all the Horsham-ites using Yelp these days.  It's probably not a bad place to be, if you're wealthy as a Czar.

While all airports are inherently bad, PHL takes it to an ever-lower rung of depravity.  Don't get me wrong, it's gorgeous, but did anyone check the plan for auto-friendliness before building?  If you're picking someone up, the road to loop back to the baggage claim area is no less than a fortnight's journey.  Not kidding.  You need GPS and knowledge of semaphore to navigate it, too.

Once inside, you may have to walk a distance once thought uncoverable by pioneers of the old west.  I thought Denver and OHare were big.  Try walking from the B concourse to the A concourse.  Bring a snack - you're going to lose a few pounds.

The all you can eat sushi is fabulous.  For $12 (lunch) or $17ish (dinner) you can stuff your face with fresh fish.  The wait staff is really friendly and the sushi is delicious (they have cooked food too, but I don't know how that is - who would pass up all you can eat sushi?).  The place is pretty small, so it gets packed, but it's worth the wait.  For sushi you can sit at the bar or at one of the tables w/bar stools, for cooked food its straight up at the tables.

Second visit: the staff was so nice today - I went to go pick up a to go order, and one of the girls that worked there hooked us up with free sodas and cookies.  I love this place!  Another great thing is you can substitute any of the toppings on the special pizzas for another topping at no charge.  The crust on the pizzas is really delicious too, I am sooo stuffed now...

the pizza toppings were really fresh and muy sabroso, and the pesto chips were actually really good - and i don't even like pesto sauce!  Skip the red sauce with the chips, just get ranch.  the people were really nice.  good food, good service.

I don't know what the hotel rooms are like, but the sushi restaurant on the bridge between the parking lot and the hotel is delish.  All you can eat sushi, around $15-16 for lunch, who knows how much for dinner.  The fish is really fresh.  You might need to wait a bit to get a seat around the sushi bar, but after you sit down the chefs are right in front of you waiting to make you whatever you want.  Only prob - the slightly creepy guys who check you out and talk amongst themselves about you.  Very unprofessional.

One of the two sushi restaurants that are the best in town.  A great place to take someone for their birthday if they like sushi... be sure and tell Sushi Hama it's their birthday.  They will wear their confetti proudly.  They do a lot of deep fried stuff here, and they have a crunchy roll that's very sweet called the Pancho Roll.  It does get busy and you may end up waiting.

This place was way more crowded than I expected it to be well before 10 on a Friday.  In fact I think it may have been close to 9 and the place was packed.  Not what I was looking for at the time, but that's cool.  I think this place is really funny as they have definitely gone for the whole tiki thing but it's so cheesy it makes it ridiculous.  They have a drink called the scorpion that is a huge bowl glass intended for two people to share.  Apparently you can order scorpions split into two glasses.  I don't recommend that, more fun if you are drinking faster trying to get your share, but I was surprised at the number of tables that had split it into two glasses.  I was also bought a tall bright red drink that was a Kon Tiki recipe, the drink was very strong but decent.

Woohoo, Sachiko is better than I remembered it.  I thought it was reasonably priced, I think an order of salmon was $2.80.  It seems you have to order soybeans though, they don't just give you some with sushi.  They have a big projection TV that annoyed me and kept catching my attention.  Dear restaurants, plz2bnoTVskthx.

It's La Salsa!  This one is bright and big inside and I noticed it has decent views if you sit by the window (you can see Wilmot/Speedway and the mountains).  Yeah, it's semi-fast Mexican, but a nice view is still a good thing.  See review of the Discount Tire in Oro Valley.

Huge awesome burritos and chimichangas, semi-fast place order and come pick it up style.  Watch out though, it can be expensive.  If you get any kind of modifications on your burrito or chimichanga, dollars are getting added.  The worst example was something like $3.75 added on for a few standard toppings like cheese, sour cream, etc.  I'd say get it without anything added on top, since they seem to put cheese and lots of other good stuff inside anyway, and you really don't want to feel like you just paid almost $10 for a burrito.

The best Greek restaurant in the area hands down.  To die for home-made Greek salad dressing that you can't find anywhere else(I've tried).  Combine this with the ample portions of their simple Greek salad and yummy potato salad and you're in heaven.  Also have generous portions for the delicious Gyros.  Other dishes are alright, but you MUST go for the salad and gyro. DOn't bother trying anything else.

Atmosphere is fantastic at any of the locations that you choose to visit.  The original one in Ybor leaves the biggest impression, but then again the one on Sand Key is right on the beach - how can you choose?  The food is fabulous, but my highest recommendations are the Cuban Sandwich, 1905 Salad, Arroz con Pollo, and side of plantains. MMmmm.... I'm a desert girl, but if I could only choose 2 I'd get the Guava Cheesecake and Flan

This restaurant, bar and music venue has been around since 1972 and has been owned by John and Peter since then!  There's live music every night of the year.  It's a great bar and a great hang to see live music.  Beware if you are fortunate enough to catch a secret hometown show by WEEN at J&P's you will be sandwiched among a ton of fans in this very small venue, but it will be an experience not to be missed.  During the summer you can dine or drink on the side outdoor patio.  Cool space and good times can be found at J&P's any night of the week.

Serves a lot of food. Huge desserts. Chocolate cake...Ummmm you keep on eating and eating and you still don't see the bottom of your plate. Just eating and eating.One peice can easily serve 3 people. Don't ask I don't share thank you.

Very casual atmosphere with a tropical flare. Wind up feelin more like you're at the islands than in FL.  Has a GREAT view of the bay and misting fans keep you from getting too hot.
I must admit - I eat more appetizers there than meals :)  You must try the Cuban Bread as it reigns supreme, other favorites include the ceviche, onion rings and habenero wings. Just thinking about it makes my stomach growl!  
 Tons of drinks to choose from (Blueberry milkshakes being my fav since i'm a non-alchol kinda gal). 
I LOVE the Tres Leche and Banana dessert that they have. MmmMmm.. so good
Fun atmoshpere.  It looks like a chain, but it's a local thing.  Unfortately, the food left something to be desired.  My portabella mushroom sandwhich was dripping with greese.  Ugh.
I was really excited to see Starbucks come to Hermitage.  My only gripe is that it's just a bit small inside - just a few tables.  All in all, though, your average Starbucks - close & convenient.
This is definitely some of the best BBQ I've had in a while. I would highly recommend their sandwhiches, but that's because I'm a BBQ sandwhich kind of guy.

I've had their sushi and their lunch special before. I wasn't too impressed with their lunch special. It just seemed to lack a little. Their sushi, on the other hand, is pretty darn good.

The atmosphere isn't anything special, but they do have a cool-looking room that seats a larger party (6-12?) in a more traditional japanese setting.

When I first visited Nashville for a tour of Belmont University years ago, the locals I knew here took me to SATCO first. I don't know if it was because it was new or what, but I loved it.

Just recently, I took a friend there for lunch. I hadn't been in awhile, but was expecting the same experience. I'll agree with Sarah - the cheese sauce is great, but the tacos I had didn't do it for me. It has moved down on my list of places to go when in that area. It is still good food, there's just better around.

This is the oldest Italian restaurant in Philadelphia.  The restaurant has been family owned and passed down from generation to generation. The poles that people use to wrap their horses around are still outside.  The food is so yummy.  It's basic no frills Italian food that is completely satisfying. The lasana, spaghetti, fettucine- it's all Italian heavan.  The prices are very reasonable. Most between $8-$15. $17 for a special.  
We spoke to one of the managing family members and just for the sheer graciousness of this fellow makes you understand why this family has been able to stay in business for so long.
If you make it out to Philly- you have to make it out there. If you live there already, you probably already have been there. If you haven't...shame on you.

This is such a great place to shop for anything. From antique books to great pastries. There is also a couple quaker stands and one of them, a eat fast diner stand, is great for breakfast...and cheap too!

The only reason this place gets any stars is because it was the only place open at 11pm. EVERYTHING closes so frickin' early in this town. The server was so cool. we loved him...a fellow student.  He is also the reason this place got any stars.  The food was terrible. If you want a real money maker in philly- open a late night pizza joint.

I adore In-N OUt burgers - get them animal style or try them in a lettuce wrap (protein style).  They've got a special menu not listed (http://www.in-n-out.com) and their fries are amazing - you can actually taste the potato in them.  Their menu is very basic but it's all you need - burgers, fries, and shakes.

Raging Sage is a desert coffee shop founded, I believe, by easterners.  I was brought there, by a midwesterner who is now of the desert, and of course I am a midwesterner now of the east.  Follow?  No?  Of course not--that was confusing.  In the same respect raging sage seems to have become a bit confused.  Per Deen (said midwesterner now of the desert) it has changed a lot over the last year, and seems to have lost that defining something that ties a coffee shop together.  The coffee was nice, but I found the lack of a dark roast somewhat vexing.  In the end I was dissastisfied and spent much of the morning starring longingly at my sister's soy latte.  The scones were solid, but not great.  A bit too moist for my taste.  In anycase it was crowded and obviously successful, but it may have lost something along the way.

Cute decor, bookshelves with random books to pass time with.  The hot chocolate sucked, but they do serve other coffee drinks which might be good (I don't drink coffee, so I couldn't say if they are actually good or not).  Also have the usual pastries/bagels/donut selection, but not a very large selection. Good prices, service was just ok.  Not many tables, but they're pretty spaced out which is nice - I hate sitting super close to other people in restaurants, and bumping them when I'm walking down the aisles.  Pretty busy morning crowd, but everyone seemed to buy and bounce.

Dark choc. Milk choc. White choc. It doesn't really matter, I'll eat it in any form. Hot chocolate, chocolate cakes, truffles, the Chocolate Bar has it all.  I loved the dark wood which surrounded the whole room, with hints of green accents here and there.  Mini tvs set into the bar, I guess if you get bored with whoever you're talking to you have something to distract you?  The overall mood is very chill, not many people when I went mid-week.  I only tried the Mayan hot choc, which has cinnamon, honey, vanilla & red peppers in it, but it was a bit too peppery for my taste.  The bar also serves cocktails, beer and sake.  Chocolate dishes include truffles (which looked really yummy), fondue, panna cotta, ice cream, cookies, and both hot and cold chocolate drinks.  I can't wait to try them all.

All I know is my sister stayed here for $25/night, and she said the rooms are bigger than the ones on Virginia St.  I think its because the Sands is old school and was built before people figured out that they could make more money by cramming more people into a smaller space.  I would add the Sands to my list of places to price in addition to the other big hotels, and its close enough to the Legacy, Circus Circus, etc. if you want to visit them as well.

One of the best places for Mexican food in Reno.  Small, family owned restaurant, great prices. Everyone who works there is really nice and patient (especially when I'm ordering for my entire family and it takes us ages to get our order in).  I love burritos, but these are totally different from the Mission burritos I'm used to.  These burritos are stuffed fat, but they aren't wrapped tightly so they're almost too hard to hold and eat.  The plates are decently sized, and there are tons of different combo options.  The ceviche reminded me of the stuff I got in Mexico, but they were a little skimpy on the avocadoes on top.  The shrimp and octopus cocktail was good, but it tasted too sweet, almost like ketchup (some people like them sweet, I'm don't particularly), not quite like the stuff I got in Mexico, but reminiscent of it and it definitely hit the spot.  Love the horchata tambien!

I had a horrible experience at this restaurant and to this day I am forever scarred by it.  I ordered the Ravioli and for some reason it took 50 minutes for me to get my entree, no joke, so strike 1.  Finally after my long wait, and filling up on bread I am anxious to tear into my dish, but it looks like a Salad, somewhere buried under the Salad or garnish, are my Ravioli, but there were only 3 of them.  Three friggin Ravioli after waiting almost an hour?!?!?!  They were regular size as well, not larger than ravioli would be.  So overall I would not suggest this place to anyone, of course I might be the rare case of food service gone wrong I have no plans to go back.  Finally any place with service that bad, and uses my favorite states name in their business, and ruining my expectations, unacceptable!  Word.

This is the best place on the mainline to get breakfast on Sunday.  You can have your Manillas and other fancy Diners, but everyone knows that after a long saturday night of partying Joe's is the Sunday morning (afternoon lol) cure!  Right on route 30 my friends and I would go ever few weeks and watch Joe run the whole kitchen, he is a artist for the breakfast crew.  Honestly it is amazing how organized they are with all the orders coming, you can take the food to go or stay in and eat.  I must say its fun to sit in and eat a large stack of pancakes or egg sandwhich with some of the regulars.  Don't let the look of the place scare you off, Joe's is the place to go for breakfast!  Word.

Very modern and chic place down in Newtown Square off of West Chester Pike.  Food and service is excellent, and the place itself is pretty cool on the inside, always a nice crowd, and in the spring its nice to grab a table outside.  If you are turned off by the sports bar place after seeing a movie, this is an excellent option.  The steak and chicken is excellent.  Bar is also a great place to have a few drinks after a day at the office, with some friends.  One of the nicer places to eat in Newtown Square.

i'd rate the food 4 stars but the service was lagging a little.  i guess smaller places aren't as used to brunch rushes as big city servers.  so the service was a little scattered.  different servers took different orders from us and in the end we had to ask a couple times for the check.  
apart from that, the servers were still friendly when they were at the table and the food was pretty good.  we had the special meatloaf and also a sausage plate.  both came with two eggs, bacon, and some potatoes.  after we ordered they brought us a basket of tasty pastries.
it was a cozy little place with tables upstairs, downstairs and outside.  inside the main floor they also have a bakery where you can buy cakes, breads, and other goodies.
i'd go back there again for the food :)

interesting menu: hawaiian-latin fusion?
the interior is a sportsbar with flat screen tvs everywhere.
it's self service so the prices of the items on the menu are relatively low.  it seems like a chain restaurant and that's what the food tastes like.  i had blackened mahi mahi, which was tasty but a tad bit salty.  the pork tacos were pretty good too...
they have an all you can eat chips and salsa bar

they have the most adorable baby/children's stuff in this place.  furnishings, strollers, clothing, playhouses, toys... 
a real cozy and cute baby boutique!

Great place to get army surplus from around the world.  I have bought many a $5-$35 jackets that have lasted me for years.  Plus they have a great camping section for those of you planning to be in the outdoors anytime soon.

A New Orleans institution, Mother's is thankfully open again post-Katrina with a limited menu. I had the shrimp po-boy and a Dixie beer, and was very satisfied. Autographed pictures of celebrities and politicians of yesterday and today line the walls. A must for any New Orleans visit.

Bertucci's Pizza's are amazing, they are all made in a brick oven (hence the name ;-) ) and I don't think I have ever been served one that is not great!  All of the food is fresh, so if you decide to go for pasta or a salad you should get a good sized portion of excellent food. I also suggest the ravioli as I have enjoyed it a few times, with a nice cold raspberry ice tea.  Of course everyone loves the fresh baked rolls that are given before the food comes, they are so good you could fill up on the rolls before your entree is served!

I've got two words for you... bedazzled turkey.  I love hitting this place up every time I go to Philly, its truely the best place to go out for a night.  Grab a tall boy of PBR and kick back in the downstairs or up.  Last trip I had we ended up there on a Sunday night and they were making hand turkeys.  I know, who the hell makes hand turkeys, well everyone at Tattooed Mom's was making turkeys.  I was so proud to see mine hanging up behind the bar the next night when I stopped by.  And all my Philly friends were making fun of it because it looked like Liberace with all the feathers and bedazzling.  Okay guys, I get it, everyone outside of SF thinks the whole city is gay.  Haha.  We're not all gay, we're all just Fabulous!  Eat that on your toast in the morning!

I'm orginally from California and I went down to Sparks for my godson's Christening. I'd heard about Sushi Pier from my cousins, brother, and uncle & they'd been raving about this and that. I was a little hesitant since it was a sushi place in the biggest little city in Nevada. Despite it being far from any pier, this sushi joint blew away all my negative expectations.

First of all, it was ALL YOU CAN EAT sushi for a mere $12! A roll by itself is about $7 already. So with the mantra of "all you can eat sushi!" in my head, I participated in gluttonous bliss. The sushi was absolutely great and differentiated itself from what I was used to in the bay. They had little twists to each of their rolls and had quirky names like the Marilyn Monroll (which I really enjoyed). If I remember correctly, the Marilyn is similar to a Philadelphia roll, but with tempura-fried tuna in the middle.. I would also try their spicy tuna handroll.. I don't really have to say anything about it.. just try it. :)

My first visit there was very enjoyable. The staff was very helpful and would substitute any sauce or ingredient for me. I enjoyed it so much that my family made the effort to go again right before we left Sparks.

Fun Fact: The walls are decked with Ramones posters and you'll find that some of the sushi rolls are named after some of the band members. Try the Joey Ramone. :)

Perfect for a college student on a budget. Cause when you got a craving for sushi, you can actually get your fix without going broke. The first time I went there in January I was struck by how friendly the staff was. Instead of just being waited on by one person, all three waitresses checked on my table. The only bad thing is that if you do all-you-can-eat lunch, you can't pick some of the fancier specialty rolls.

This rating is based on the hamburgers alone. They are freakin huge and piled with goodies. Probably the I don't know what they do to their patties, but they are so juicy and delish. Be sure to try the onion rings, which you can substitute for instead of fries. A burger and fries costs about $7 or $8 if I remember right, but it's worth it if you want to get away from all that fast food crap. I haven't had breakfast yet, though I hear it's good. Remember they only stay open till about 3 p.m. each day.

Yay for fried food. This place has got some pretty good buffalo wings and good portions. The staff is friendly. There are pool tables, a jukebox and TVs running all sorts of sporting events. Decent neighborhood bar hangout. Been there a couple times and it's never too crowded.

In any given city, Residence Inn tends to be located a stone's throw - or two - from where the action is, but that's a minor inconvenience if you have access to a car or a good public transportation system. This property is ideal for families or friends who would like some privacy or a little extra space to spread out. Accommodations are in studio, one-, and two-bedroom (two-bath) apartments, with fully-equipped kitchens and comfortable living rooms with a dining area. Amenities include satellite TV with premium channels, video games, and pay-to-view movies, phone with dataport and voice mail, and a fireplace in select units. There's a swimming pool and fitness center with cardiovascular equipment and free weights on-site. Rates - which vary by season and day of the week, but generally start at $129 - include a buffet breakfast and an evening reception with complimentary cocktails and snacks.

Located in the Atlantis, this buffet is fairly standard for breakfast, lunch, and most dinners . . . but seafood lovers should head here on Friday nights for a special treat. In addition to the usual array of salads, cold cuts, and the regular stations offering specialties from Mexico, Asia, Italy, and the like, you'll be facing mounds of crabs, clams, mussels, shrimp, and assorted fish in a wide variety of hot and cold preparations. Skip breakfast and lunch so you can fill up enough to justify the $23.95 price tag for what is probably the best way to say TGIF in town.

Cute BYOB right off of Rittenhouse square. It's usually pretty crowded and for good reason, the Mediterranean inspired cuisine is original and delicious. The menu is seasonal using meats and vegetables that the chef thinks are most fresh during that particular season. The menu is divided into 4 parts: flat breads, antipasta, small dishes, and large dishes. The flat breads typically have some cheese and vegetables. They seem to be a big hit, but weren't my thing because I only like simple cheese (yes, all cheese lovers can cringe). The small dishes provide a nice variety and include some salads. I had the PEI mussels which were perfectly cooked and a generous portion. The large dishes are mostly meats/poultry/fish though I think there was a vegetarian one. Most come with a starch of some sort. I had chicken with pomegranite molasses which was amazing. Pefectly cooked. The salmon and lamb my friends had were excellent as well. Desserts must rotate pretty often because they are written on a chalk board nearby. We split blackberry-apple bread pudding which was outstanding. I pretty much wanted to try all of them. IIRC there was also pumpkin pie, vanilla risotto pudding, and a pot de creme. Definitely worth checking out and very reasonably priced. The only downside for me besides not loving the pita breads was that they don't take credit cards.

The burgers here are great, but what surprised me was the onion rings.  I am a hardcore hater of onion rings, yet for some reason I'm optimistic enough to try them every time someone orders them.  I have yet to meet an onion ring that I have liked, but today I met my match at Archie's.  I don't know what it was about them - they were kinda sweet?  they didn't have that horribly overpowering oniony taste?  Just get 'em.  And eat 'em with the ranch.  Everything else was good too, nice milkshake, not too thick so you can't suck it up through your little ole straw, but not all runny and disgusting like some places.  The chili cheese fries were good too, although I like my fries big and crispy and these were a little too small for me.  But everything was tasty enough to earn it those big five stars.  *Things to look for when you go: check out the two celeb pictures by the door, its kinda crazy to think that these people actually ate at Archie's.  Actually, its crazy to think these people were out here in Reno.  What the hell were they doing here?  The rest of the decor is kinda lacking, but who cares really?  All you want to do is sit in a comfy booth, eat a fat burger and a shake, and hang out.  The real question is, where's Jughead?
It is comforting to know that my hometown can call this steakhouse home. St. Elmo has the best shrimp cocktail on this planet--May edge it's local rival "Mortons of Chicago" on app/atmostphere alone.

Wander through to the back; that dingy diner counter is home to the most amazing of burgers, the Awful Awful -- a tasty burger served on a bed of skinny seasoned french fries.  It's mighty fine.

The place can get really packed, but it's so worth it.

Nice rooms, super-gaudy casino floor, good restaurtants.  Upgrade to a spa suite with a bar and you may never leave the room.  The buffet is easily one of the best in Reno, and the Peppermill Coffee Shop is just the place for a late night snack.

This buffet and the one at the Peppermill are easily the best in town.  The Mexican station has some pretty spicy food for a buffet (especially the little tacos, which are tasty and quite popular, so grab some when you see them).  The salad bar area is large and has really delicious mixed salads as well as the do-it-yourself lettuce and fixings area. Also, when I was there, the salad bar has the freshest, sweetest melons and strawberries.

Oh yeah - it's been since the early 90's since I've been to CLUB CONGRESS - during my college years - great place to see bands too.  it's located inside a hotel and not very big - unless it's been remodeled ofcourse.  Seen greats shows here: GAYE BYKERS ON ACID, JON SPENCER BLUES XPLOSION, GOO GOO DOLLS ( when they played way faster ) SIDEWINDERS and a good number of kick ass bands.  i'm sure it's still the "cool" place to be.

I don't want to acknowledge how beautiful and perfect this place is b/c I have no idea when we will ever be able to afford go back.  My now-husband wisked me away to Santa Barbara the weekend we got engaged.  We stayed at the Bacara. In fact, the very picture on my profile was taken that weekend on the beach just steps away from our room, which was, by the way, the nicest hotel room I have ever stayed in.  It had a wonderful balcony that you could see the ocean from.  So romantic. There were huge vases of calla lillies all over the place.  Beautiful pools.  Trust me, I usually go for tiny hotels - like under 30 rooms.  I don't like the Four Seasons in Santa Barbara or the Princess is Scottsdale.  But I looooved the Bacara.  I could go on and on and on...  oh, and the tar on the beach is natural.  It is from the seeps.

Roaches, schmoaches.  A true Philly boy took us to this dive right after a visit to Jim's.  Another buddy saw a roach happily greeting us at the doorstep, but that didn't stop us from enjoying one of the best slices of pizza, ever.  The slice was much bigger than my face and once I folded that baby and took a bite, my heart whimpered in defeat.  Lorenzo's is the best way to happily clog your arteries. YUM!
Like another review, there was a problem with my repair (the valve on a new tire was faulty), but they promptly took care of it and were really friendly.
The service here is excellent and the staff is very knowledgeable.  The downside is that they tend to be very busy.  Your best bet is to get an appointment at least a few days in advance.

My wife and I were craving Indian, but didn't want to drive into the city.  We probably should have.  The food isn't bad, but not really good either.  If you care more about Indian atmosphere than the quality of the food, you might like it.  It appears to be regularly frequented by many Indians in the area.

This restaurant is huge and when other places are packed on a weekend, you can usually get in here.  The food is typical Mexican fare, maybe a little more authentic than most chain restuarants, but not particularly notable.  Pretty good overall.

This was the first time I ate Korean food, so all I can say was that it is the best Korean food I have ever had in my entire life.  : D  It was really good, though, go.  Someone else got fried squid.  It was ridiculously good.  I'll get that next time.

I like this place cause it's a laid back, no fuss establishment. If you're looking for something fun to do, but don't want to "dress to impress" head here for beer, pizza and wings. Chow down on fried mushrooms or zucchini at picnic tables scattered about the restaurant. I've been here to watch a couple of Wolf Pack bball games, which always gets the crowd going. I think on Friday nights you can get 1/2 priced pizzas from 6-9 p.m. (I think...)

This is the best diner I've been to. In fact, so good, that I went twice in one day - for dinner before a concert a Sovereign Bank Arena, and afterwards for a midnight snack. A lot of eateries around here look totally sketchy, but when I saw that Pat's was packed, I thought I'd take a shot. Delicious, affordable, and service was great. A must for a hungry person passing through Trenton.

Uh? How can this record store suck?  Sure, it's not for mainstream music nor do they have much international music but this record/cd joint has loads of independent music.  IF you want Modanna go to the mall or those corporate retail chains.  If you're looking for SUN KIL MOON, you are at the right place.
Pretty good selection.  The system also has a surprising number of good DVDs available for borrowing.
You've got to try this place at least once for the experience.  Besides the coolness factor, the food is actually pretty good for the price.

May be the best cheap eats in town...well except for John & Peter's...but this is the place where Gene Ween worked as a teen and was inspired to write "Pollo Asado" from The Pod!  Any Ween fan will enjoy a basket of cheeeps from this place.  

Do you make guacamole?  Yes, I do make guacamole.

Decent-good Chinese food, very posh decor, and excellent service which is probably why they can charge as much as they do ($7-11/dish).  When I decided I wanted Chinese food for dinner, I was shocked to be brought to Palais de Jade.  The first thing you notice when you walk in is the beautiful bar, with a slightly older crowd sitting around drinking cognac and wine (I felt a bit out of place until I saw a couple of families with younger kids sitting around enjoying their meals). The service was really impressive (especially after years of crappy restaurants around colleges) - at least four waiters were constantly checking on our table throughout the night, and our water glasses were never empty.  We ordered the westlake beef soup - delicious, the minced beef practically melted in our mouths and was perfectly seasoned - maybe the best I've ever had, lemon chicken - lightly coated and deep fried, but not at all oily, mongolian beef - not very spicy, but well flavored, chicken fried rice - slightly dry, but yummy and had huge pieces of chicken, and tofu, black mushrooms and snow peas - which was in a gravy that I didn't really like, but wasn't too bad all in all.  The drink menu also had champagne in addition to the wine and liquers - I also saw a couple with some margarita looking drinks that looked super good, but I wasn't in the mood when I went.  After trying a few other places in Reno that weren't that hot, I would definitely recommend Palais de Jade.  Hell, I'd go there again just for the service.

Seriously now. Hands down the BEST Pad Thai in the city. It can get a little pricey but the fried tofu plate as an appetizer is awesome. I think it's like 5 buck for a HUGE plate of tofu, the first time I went there i saw some lady get it and I was so bummed I didn't order it becuse it was seriously like a brick and a half worth of fried goodness, just get extra sauces particularly the peanut sauce.

This is probably the best burritto in phily...sadly that's not sayin' much. They're like 8 dollars and come in a plethora options. If your vegan the Faux-beef minus cheese is pretty damn tasty but seeing how the last place I lived before here was boston I'm used to bigass burittos and these hardly match up. However like I said these are the best burittos that I've found so far.
Holy mother of god. Go here. Amazing vegan and meateater options alike . 'nough said.

Granted I don't eat cheese so reviwing a pizza joint is a little off, but myself and all the other vegans and ex-vegans I know swear by the alegro tomato pie. It's fricken delicious. Beare in mind this place in university city so your going to have to put up with more drunk jocks then you can shake a stick at but hey if you can't beat 'em join 'em...alegros sells beer.
The bar is OK.  It's nice looking, but has a manufactured feel like a lot of other new restaurants.  Very Ikea.

Never been here for dinner, but it's a great place to hit for nightlife!! The crowd pours in a bit late, as you'd expect from a college town, but then there are people everywhere. If you want a booth, show up early. The "bucket" drinks are great! They serve HUGE drinks in a 80 oz bucket. Split between two people, you'll be buzzin' awhile! The music is okay, worth dancing to... especially after a 'bucket'.
Traditional college hangout with the crowd to match (young, fun).

THE best steak around!! It's the stuff of legend! Fork tender and melts in your mouth! I started with filet mignon bites served with a buttery dipping sauce and moved onto a perfect new york strip with sauteed mushrooms. Out of this world good! And not outrageously expensive for the quality of food! Out of the price range of many students however, so you'll likely find some quiet here; a rarity on State St.

Often live music, and a true BAR feel. it's not trying to be a lounge, or a club, or an oversized VIP area. It knows it's a bar and does well at it. Can get crowded, but what place doesn't in a college town? I had hoped for a little more personality from a place named after Joyce, but really nothing made it stand out from hundreds of other bars I've been to.

Visit today: Such a disappointment. Looks like I'm never going here again. The story: A woman tried cutting me in line today and then complained to the cashier. Apparently the cashier put in The Jerk's order first to please her. I watched in disgust as The Jerk's daughter carted away an order that was much larger than the one I ordered. When I asked another employee about my order, she looked at me, yawned and then began filling up sodas. I was pissed as I ate my burrito. The food may be cheap, but the service sucks.

First visit: OK, I just found out about this place last week and I've already been there twice. But what's not to love about a 24-hour Mexican restaurant that beats Taco Bell and Del Taco any day of the week?! Nothing. That's what I thought. Let's see, a pretty good-sized burrito is $3.25. It's $0.29 more for cheese and sour cream (each). I'm also a fan of the meat plate, which is a scoop of rice, beans, meat of your choice, lettuce and four or five tortillas for $3.99. I know, you're mouth is watering right? I have yet to try the chorizo and eggs or huevos rancheros, (both $4.99) but I was told they only serve it in the morning until 11 a.m.

As for the dining area, it's got lots of tables and booths. It's nothing special to look at, well, except for the old school arcade games (i.e. Street Fighter and Pac Man).

So the next time you crave a Mexican pizza or Baja chalupa, slap yourself across the face, tell yourself Taco Bell sucks and try this joint. Your tastebuds will say "gracias."

I love Dali.  He's my favorite surrealist and probably my favorite non-musical artist.  You can not look at Dali's work and not agree that he was a genius.  Well, I suppose you could but come on, do you really think that or are you just saying that because everyone loves Dali?

There is maybe not much to do in St. Petersburg, Fl but, by God, they have the Salvador Dali Museum and that counts for something in my book.

The interior is ultra-modern and very cool.  I like how the colors of the lights constantly change adding a new dimension to the experience.  I went with 3 friends while we were in town for a conference and we decided to go all out.  

We ordered a couple of entrees.  The seafood stew thing was awful and nothing special.  Then we went with a huge order of a sushi assortment plate.  

The nigiri was pretty delicious with very fresh fish.  Some of them I had never tried before.  

Then we rolled with the dessert.  The wasabi tiramisu was heavenly, the wasabi kicks in at the very end of each bite.  Nicely done.  The chocolate mousse was delicious too.

The desserts were probably the highlight of the evening.  The sushi was great and fresh but not too inventive, I guess out in Philly it might be a big deal since they don't have many sushi restaurants?  They also charged far too much for supermarket quality sake.

While visiting Philly, we stopped by this place and had a really great time.    Downstairs they have a long bar and upstairs there are a few tables and another bar area.  It's very laidback and casual.  

Their menu consists of about 200 beers (international) with about 15 on tap.  They also have ratings and alcohol content on the menu.  We really had no idea what to get but the waitress was really nice and helpful.  I ended up with La Chouffe served in a huge glass goblet.  It was amazing!  Sorta like a hefe but a little more sweet and smooth.  

They serve food too but didn't try any of it.  All in all, a nice place to hang out and try some new beers.

The service was excellent, the ambiance/decor was beautiful, the food was delicious, and the belly dancers were great entertainment!  

Chef Karim greeted us personally and made sure we enjoyed our experience.   Thanks to him, and the staff, our party had a wonderful time.  

I highly recommend this restaurant, especially for large groups.

If you've ever watched Iron Chef, you know that Morimoto is a culinary genius. As expected, his restaurant didn't disappoint. You walk into the restaurant and are surrounded by cold white furniture illuminated with cycling colored lights. They have a list of asian inspired cocktails which turned out to be unique and strong: we had ones based on saki and green tea. Obviously sushi is prevalent on the menu given Morimoto's background, but the other Japanese style dishes like tempura with gorgonzola and the cooked fish dishes were incredible. We're big scallop fans and the hotate sushi was the best we have ever had, narrowly beating out a few places in Japan. Desserts were a little less impresive with a wasabi tiramisu being a very weird blend of flavors. Next time I go back, I will definitely try the chef's tasting menu, though we opted not to on this occasion since Morimoto, himself, was not there.

Coming from the West Coast, I was having serious Mexican food withdrawal. A friend introduced me to Tequila's and I have to say it is far and away the most authentic Veracruz style Mexican in Philly. It's right up there with El Vez as the best in my book. They have ample seating in the back for large parties, and good service. I almost felt like I was back in California while drinking the large margaritas, which the waitstaff carry on their heads. We also had some damn good sangria along with our meal of typical Mexican style fare. The seafood was particularly good here compared with other Mexican restaurants in Philadelphia.

One of the best brunch places in Philadelphia. If you go you absolutely must get the monkey bread, which is this warm, sugary, dough. Absolutely addicting.  They have a good mix of sweet and savory brunch food, though I think the sweets there are the best. The BMW (banana, maple, walnut) pancakes were great. They also give you quite a bit of freedom in customizing your meal including a generous selection of fillings for making your own omelette.

Pumpkin is one of the hot spots right now for BYOB. It's located in a small cramped space on South Street. The first thing I noticed was the small menu, it's good in that the chef tries to only make dishes with fresh ingredients, but bad in that it seriously limits your dining options. What I most remember was the good sauces that accompanied the decent cooking: my quail had a nice balsamic reduction and scallops had a saffron vermouth sauce. The wait staff was a little pushy, but all in all it was a good meal and definitely has a different sort of a menu than some of the other BYOs around.

Tangerine is Starr's take on Mediterranean food. Let me start by saying that most like this play much better than I do. Many would give it 5 stars. Like most Starr restaurants Tangerine has a fun list of cocktails to choose from. Tangerine's drink menu has mainly upscale martinis, which were very good. Dinner was a mixed plate with the chef fully utilizing mediterranean flavors in items like chickpea crepes, pistacchio/raisin bread, shrimp afrique, moroccan shrimp, and red ssnapper with red pepper sauce. These flavors carried over to dessert as well in a pistacchio ice cream. It's not that Tangerine wasn't good, but it was just a little too unidimensional for me. I didn't think the flavors meshed as well together as at some of the other Starr restaurants.

One thing I will say about Fork is that it is much quieter than some of the other dining places around. I had an excellent meal here, tucked into a comfortable corner of the restaurant. The service was excellent with the waiter knowing all the details of the menu. All the food was exceedingly fresh and you will find many ingredients that you don't find on other menues. We started with a mushroom flatbread that was excellent. A blue nose bass and parchment wrapped, coconut-miso salmon were cooked perfectly and full of flavor. They also have several sides which are good additions to the meal, including honey roasted sweet potatoes. Dessert was out of control good: pumpkin cheesecake and apple-cranberry cobbler with vanilla gelato. There was nothing left on the dessert plates when we were done. Highly recommended.

Oh how I wish my name was Fred.

That's the name of the guy who started this yummy pizza chain. If you're named Fred, you get some kinda deals on stuff there. What is it you ask? Well, I don't know. My name isn't Fred. But for any Freds out there, do let me know.

I first was introduced to this place because of the pesto chips ($4). The chips come shaped about the size of a personal pizza and covered in gooey cheese and pesto sauce. The flavor is not too overbearing and it's a nice little snack if you don't have much money. Ask for ranch.

I agree that the crust is actually good. It's kind of buttery, soft, doughy and doesn't taste like that burnt excuse for pizza crust that most chains serve. While all the toppings are good, I really like the sausage here. I knew the food was good here when a friend of mine who hates pizza tried some of my leftovers and then asked if we could order an x-large pizza to go. Convert the non-believers is what I say.

It has been a little while since I last visited the Four Seasons in Philadelphia, but it was everything one would expect from a Four Seasons hotel. The suites are large and comfortable enough to seat four or five. Housekeeping comes twice a day no matter how big of a mess you manage to make. There is internet access in every room and it was easy enough to get going. The staff seemed to bend over backwards to ensure my stay was pleasant.

Everything is decorated in early Americana. I guess it fits with Philadelphia.

The hotel itself is close to both the financial and retail areas. The downside? Pat's, Geno's and Jim's cheesesteak shops are over 7 miles away! Well luckily, there are cabs in Philly that will get you to that wiz covered goodness quick enough. :)

Good Lord how could some many art treasures exist in one building.  Vermeer only painted under 40 paintings- 2 or 3 are in here. The Whistler and Sargent pieces (one of the most seductive and dark pieces of Sargent's career and an embarrasment to the socialite's who commissioned the piece family- she loved it- they strove to hide it. Eventually it was the first Sargent to be publicly purchased and displayed in any museum). Also, if you love epic pieces they have a great piece that depicts an old 19th century medical lecture where all the students are watching the body being examined- I believe by Thomas Eakins. It stands an impressive 15-20 ft high and even more ft wider. A beautiful Winslow Homer collection. Also they have the most STUNNING period world reconsruction rooms of Imperial China, Japan and French Louis the someteenth. 
When you're here, save the time to see some real treasures and avoid the Rocky trap. We went, we saw and were let down with those steps.  We were going to refilm the running up the steps and pumping the arms, but saw all the other losers doing it and thought better of it.
Oh- if you get a chance and it's there that day, the corn chowder was INCREDIBLE.

If you make it too Philly- try to make it here. My friend is a doctor and suggested it and we were not disappointed. You can see the soap lady, apparently when fatty bodies decompose in certain environments they turn to soap (soap is made from fats and oils). Also there is a cast of the famous chinese siamese twins. There is a collection of skulls that psychiatrists studied to see if there was a correlation between people's traits and cranial structure (includes 50 + skulls on various murderers, rapists, hardened criminals). Also contains various murdered skeletal remains like axe wounds etc.  A pretty full collection of embryos. all sorts of shrunken heads and models of various medical conditions from frostbite to jaundice. Cancerous growths. The tallest skeletal remains and the shortest skeletal remains.  
$12 I think to get in.  Kinda pricey. I think they have student discounts.

I gotta agree with Andrew S. This is a terrible airport. In addition to all the problems mentioned by Andrew, the layout sucks too. In particular, Terminal D (which appears to be mainly American Airlines, the biggest airline in this airport) is a super long terminal that just goes on and on. Although it has some people escalators, it can take forever to make it from one end to to the other. If possible, avoid flying through here.

A nice pub located in the Central West End of St. Louis. On the weekends, they have live music in their main room. I thought the prices were on the higher end for STL, but, they did have a decent selection of beers on tap. In addition, they have your standard pub grub - burgers, etc. I didn't eat here so I have no idea if its any good.

Hey-- it's a diner.  You were expecting maybe gourmet cuisine?!

Enter hungry.

It's OK.  It's even good.  You sure get a lot of food for your money.  Surprisingly wide selection at the salad bar.  Big menu, very reasonably priced.  Lots of complete dinners.  Even better prices if you catch the Early Bird Specials.  Lots of handsome desserts, too.  And don't forget breakfast and lunch, too.  Be sure to read the billboards on the parking-lot wall.

You gotta love the '50s dinerness of the decor, gotta love the experience.

Smaller than the average diner.  It's on a congested (by local standards) shopping street, but there's off-street parking.  Quaker Diner is half a block from Five Points (intersection of Rising Sun, Oxford, and Cottman Aves.), so there are lots of buses nearby.  Heck, I've even WALKED there!

They're good people-- they donate catering to events at the Lawndale Methodist Church a block or two down Cottman Ave.  I'm no Methodist, but I go to some of the community meetings where local politicians give talks and Q&A sessions-- and afterwards help myself to a platter of that Quaker Diner catering while I shmooze with the other civic-minded souls.

So much good about the place... I'm gonna give them an extra star!
